,"nl":{"1220–1272":"1220–1272","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1244–1298":"1244–1298","1248":"1248","Abt 1260":"circa 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","after 1244":"na 1244","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Schotland","Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dundaff Castle, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1220–1272":"1220–1272","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1244–1298":"1244–1298","1248":"1248","Abt 1260":"about 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","after 1244":"after 1244","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dundaff Castle, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"David Graham was born in 1220, in Stirlingshire, Scotland. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Noble. In 1264, at the age of 44, his occupation is listed as sheriff of berwick. He died in 1272, in Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1220–1272":"1220–1272","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1244–1298":"1244–1298","1248":"1248","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","after 1244":"pärast 1244","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dundaff Castle, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1220–1272":"1220–1272","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1244–1298":"1244–1298","1248":"1248","Abt 1260":"noin 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","after 1244":"1244 jälkeen","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dundaff Castle, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1220–1272":"1220–1272","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1244–1298":"1244–1298","1248":"1248","Abt 1260":"environ 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","after 1244":"après 1244","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Écosse","Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Dundaff Castle, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"David Graham est né en 1220, à Stirlingshire, Écosse. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Agnes Noble. En 1264, à l’âge de 44 ans, sa profession de son indiquée est sheriff of berwick. Il est décédé en 1272, à Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 52 ans."},"de":{"1220–1272":"1220–1272","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1244–1298":"1244–1298","1248":"1248","Abt 1260":"um 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","after 1244":"nach 1244","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Kilmorack, Invern